{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01612uUnMKvjoahJiPxkdNWo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see that the `buildOpentelemetry` function generates the OTel config. This is a Go template function that generates the TOML config. The controller binary's source code would define exactly what keys it reads from the ConfigMap.\n\nLet me look at what `buildOpentelemetry` generates by looking at the existing nginx.conf (but it won't be there since OTel is not enabled). Let me check the ingress-nginx source code documentation for the exact ConfigMap keys.\n\nBased on my knowledge of ingress-nginx:\nThe ConfigMap keys for OpenTelemetry in ingress-nginx v1.x are:\n- `enable-opentelemetry: \"true\"` to activate it\n- `opentelemetry-config: \"/etc/nginx/opentelemetry.toml\"` pointing to the config file\n- `otlp-collector-host` and `otlp-collector-port` specifying where to send traces\n- `otel-sampler` to control sampling strategy (like AlwaysOn)\n- `otel-sampler-ratio` for ratio-based sampling\n- `otel-sampler-parent-based` to disable parent-based sampling\n- `otel-service-name` identifying the service as \"nginx\"\n\nThe controller generates OpenTelemetry directives that set operation names based on the request method and URI, plus mark sensitive headers like authorization and cookies. The TOML configuration file itself is created by the controller based on ConfigMap settings and placed at the specified path, rather than being templated directly.\n\nNow I'm ready to apply the ConfigMap update using kubectl patch to enable OpenTelemetry with the collector host, port, sampling strategy, and service name configured.\n\nI also need to create the Ingress for otel.example.com to route traffic to the backend, and I'll format the custom log format string to include the OpenTelemetry trace and span ID variables.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_to